The North Star (1943) 1hr 48min

2
00:01:25,652 --> 00:01:28,154
Good morning, my
little honey bees.

3
00:01:28,155 --> 00:01:30,156
Good morning!

4
00:01:30,157 --> 00:01:32,158
Good morning. Good morning.

5
00:01:32,159 --> 00:01:33,661
Good morning, one and all.

6
00:01:33,662 --> 00:01:35,661
Good... Morning!

7
00:01:35,662 --> 00:01:37,164
Good morning!

8
00:01:55,682 --> 00:01:58,184
Anna!

9
00:01:58,185 --> 00:01:59,186
Anna!

10
00:01:59,686 --> 00:02:00,686
Anna!

11
00:02:00,687 --> 00:02:02,188
Where's Pavel Grigorich?

12
00:02:02,189 --> 00:02:04,190
I've come to be your
guest for breakfast.

13
00:02:04,191 --> 00:02:05,191
Stop shouting.

14
00:02:05,192 --> 00:02:06,694
Don't be so young
with the voice.

15
00:02:07,194 --> 00:02:08,696
You'll have to come
back, Comrade Karp.

16
00:02:08,697 --> 00:02:10,196
Grandpa is still asleep.

17
00:02:10,197 --> 00:02:12,700
A new baby came to the
hospital last night,

18
00:02:12,701 --> 00:02:14,700
and then Grandpa came
home and did his writing.

19
00:02:14,701 --> 00:02:15,701
Good morning.

20
00:02:15,702 --> 00:02:18,204
That's not the way you say it.

21
00:02:18,205 --> 00:02:21,207
You say, "a baby came
into the bright world

22
00:02:21,208 --> 00:02:24,712
in the darkest part
of the night."

23
00:02:26,213 --> 00:02:28,714
Don't talk so pretty.

24
00:02:28,715 --> 00:02:30,716
A new baby. Isn't that nice?

25
00:02:30,717 --> 00:02:32,218
What's nice about it?

26
00:02:32,219 --> 00:02:33,220
I -- I'll be back.

27
00:02:33,720 --> 00:02:35,721
You argue too much.

28
00:02:35,722 --> 00:02:37,723
Heep!

29
00:02:37,724 --> 00:02:39,225
Good morning, Grandpa.

30
00:02:39,226 --> 00:02:41,729
Ah. Good morning, my lad.

31
00:02:52,739 --> 00:02:54,741
You should not have
worked all night.

32
00:02:55,242 --> 00:02:57,243
Mm. I had a good night's work.

33
00:02:57,244 --> 00:02:59,245
Did a little writing.

34
00:02:59,246 --> 00:03:00,746
Feel better? Mm-hmm.

35
00:03:00,747 --> 00:03:02,749
Come and have breakfast now.

36
00:03:03,750 --> 00:03:04,751
Oh, dear.

37
00:03:09,756 --> 00:03:12,758
What seems to be the
trouble, Boris Stepanich?

38
00:03:12,759 --> 00:03:15,761
It'll take a better mechanic
than I am to answer that.

39
00:03:15,762 --> 00:03:18,264
The patient is cured, Father.

40
00:03:18,265 --> 00:03:19,265
It's all right now.

41
00:03:19,266 --> 00:03:20,766
Hello, Comrade Karp.

42
00:03:20,767 --> 00:03:22,768
You ever been to Kiev?
Of course.

43
00:03:22,769 --> 00:03:25,772
There was a pretty girl there
who lost her head over me.

44
00:03:26,273 --> 00:03:28,274
Years ago. Oh, of course.

45
00:03:28,275 --> 00:03:31,277
Well, it is the
last day of school.

46
00:03:31,278 --> 00:03:33,279
Tomorrow morning,
we'll be on our way.

47
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:36,282
It's our vacation, and we're
going to Kiev on a holiday.

48
00:03:36,283 --> 00:03:37,785
That's a nice bus ride.

49
00:03:37,786 --> 00:03:39,285
Not for us. We're hiking.

50
00:03:39,286 --> 00:03:41,288
All the way? Well, of course.

51
00:03:41,788 --> 00:03:43,289
It'll only take us
four or five days.

52
00:03:43,290 --> 00:03:44,790
Only?

53
00:03:44,791 --> 00:03:46,292
Marina is going?

54
00:03:46,293 --> 00:03:49,295
Yes. Marina and
Clavdia and grisha.

55
00:03:49,296 --> 00:03:51,797
My brother -- unfortunately.

56
00:03:51,798 --> 00:03:55,302
Ah, but Marina is
the one who counts.

57
00:03:56,803 --> 00:03:57,803
Have you proposed?

58
00:03:57,804 --> 00:04:00,806
Or does one propose in
these modern times?

59
00:04:00,807 --> 00:04:02,308
Good morning, Papa.

60
00:04:02,309 --> 00:04:03,811
Good morning.

61
00:04:10,817 --> 00:04:12,818
What are you doing, Marina?

62
00:04:12,819 --> 00:04:14,820
I'm baking honey
cakes for the trip.

63
00:04:14,821 --> 00:04:16,822
The cakes have
to be baked now?

64
00:04:16,823 --> 00:04:19,325
You're not leaving
until tomorrow.

65
00:04:19,326 --> 00:04:20,828
Well, it's hard at our age

66
00:04:20,829 --> 00:04:22,829
to remember how
exciting a trip can be.

67
00:04:23,330 --> 00:04:25,332
The planning is half the fun.

68
00:04:28,335 --> 00:04:30,838
A long time ago, this is
the way I wore my hair.

69
00:04:31,338 --> 00:04:33,841
Were you pretty, Mama,
when you were young?

70
00:04:33,842 --> 00:04:35,841
I'm not so old, little one.

71
00:04:35,842 --> 00:04:38,345
Mama's pretty now.
And she's not old.

72
00:04:38,845 --> 00:04:40,346
It's only that
you're so young.

73
00:04:40,347 --> 00:04:42,348
I'm not so young.

74
00:04:42,349 --> 00:04:43,851
There are plenty
who are younger.

75
00:04:43,852 --> 00:04:45,352
Yes. And there always will be.

76
00:04:47,854 --> 00:04:51,357
Sophia, when you go marketing,
remind everybody to come

77
00:04:51,358 --> 00:04:53,861
and help with the
loading of the trains.

78
00:04:53,862 --> 00:04:55,861
Tell them there will
be supper for all

79
00:04:55,862 --> 00:04:56,902
when the work is finished.

80
00:04:57,364 --> 00:04:59,365
I'll tell everybody!
I'll tell everybody!

81
00:04:59,366 --> 00:05:00,866
May I, Papa? May I?

82
00:05:00,867 --> 00:05:02,868
I'll do it on my
way to school.

83
00:05:02,869 --> 00:05:04,370
Please, may I? May I, please?

84
00:05:04,371 --> 00:05:06,372
All right. You tell them.

85
00:05:06,373 --> 00:05:08,374
I'll say there will be
supper for everybody.

86
00:05:08,375 --> 00:05:09,375
Yes.

87
00:05:09,376 --> 00:05:11,879
I'll say there will
be music and singing.

88
00:05:11,880 --> 00:05:13,379
I'll say there
will be dancing,

89
00:05:13,380 --> 00:05:15,381
and I'll say there will
be cider for old people

90
00:05:15,382 --> 00:05:16,882
and fruit drinks for children.

91
00:05:16,883 --> 00:05:18,885
You might also remember to
say there will be work.

92
00:05:20,387 --> 00:05:21,887
Oh.

93
00:05:21,888 --> 00:05:23,889
Yes. I'll say that, too.

94
00:05:23,890 --> 00:05:27,894
"Everybody must
work," I'll say.

95
00:05:28,895 --> 00:05:30,896
No pancakes?

96
00:05:30,897 --> 00:05:33,899
You know what else the comrade
commander said to me?

97
00:05:33,900 --> 00:05:36,402
You have my permission
not to tell me.

98
00:05:36,403 --> 00:05:38,404
"Eat pancakes."
That's what he said.

99
00:05:38,405 --> 00:05:40,406
It has been
recently discovered

100
00:05:40,407 --> 00:05:42,910
that pancakes are fine for
a bombardier's nerves.

101
00:05:42,911 --> 00:05:44,410
That ought to
interest you, Damian.

102
00:05:44,411 --> 00:05:45,913
You're going to be a doctor.

103
00:05:45,914 --> 00:05:48,914
It doesn't interest me.

104
00:05:48,915 --> 00:05:50,916
Don't worry with
those maps, Damian.

105
00:05:50,917 --> 00:05:52,418
I know all the roads.

106
00:05:52,419 --> 00:05:53,921
And when we get to Kiev,

107
00:05:53,922 --> 00:05:57,424
I will show you and your little
friends all there is to see.

108
00:05:57,924 --> 00:06:00,926
Me and my little friends
are still young.

109
00:06:00,927 --> 00:06:01,927
A visit to Kiev

110
00:06:01,928 --> 00:06:04,430
is something that doesn't
happen to us every day.

111
00:06:04,431 --> 00:06:06,932
And don't patronize
us about it.

112
00:06:06,933 --> 00:06:08,934
Be a man of the world in
front of your mirror.

113
00:06:08,935 --> 00:06:10,936
It's better that way.
Mirrors don't talk back.

114
00:06:10,937 --> 00:06:12,438
Hmm!

115
00:06:12,439 --> 00:06:15,943
Most men in the world feel
pleased when they have sons.

116
00:06:15,944 --> 00:06:16,943
I wonder why.

117
00:06:16,944 --> 00:06:18,944
I told you years ago.

118
00:06:18,945 --> 00:06:21,947
Two quiet little girls
would have been very nice.

119
00:06:21,948 --> 00:06:24,950
Well, you can't change us now,
and you wouldn't if you could.

120
00:06:24,951 --> 00:06:27,953
Two healthy, brilliant,
handsome sons.

121
00:06:27,954 --> 00:06:30,956
June 20, 1941, 8:00 A.M.,

122
00:06:30,957 --> 00:06:32,958
broadcasting from moscow.
Be still, both of you.

123
00:06:32,959 --> 00:06:37,963
German troop movements are
reported on the Polish border.

124
00:06:37,964 --> 00:06:39,965
Their nature is unknown.

125
00:06:39,966 --> 00:06:41,967
Reports reach us of
a typhus epidemic

126
00:06:41,968 --> 00:06:43,969
in the German-occupied
city of Warsaw.

127
00:06:43,970 --> 00:06:46,973
London was bombed twice last
night by the Luftwaffe.

128
00:06:47,474 --> 00:06:48,976
In the Polish city of Lodz,

129
00:06:48,977 --> 00:06:52,478
112 Polish children died
this morning as a result

130
00:06:52,479 --> 00:06:55,983
of being made to give blood
transfusions to German wounded.

131
00:06:55,984 --> 00:06:58,984
Children. Taking blood from...

132
00:06:58,985 --> 00:07:01,488
Here's a report from a
reliable source in --

133
00:07:21,007 --> 00:07:22,007
goodbye, now.

134
00:07:22,008 --> 00:07:23,008
Goodbye, sweetheart.

135
00:07:23,009 --> 00:07:24,010
Goodbye, Papa. Bye, baby.

136
00:07:24,511 --> 00:07:26,512
Goodbye, Papa.

137
00:07:26,513 --> 00:07:28,015
Bye, Mama. Bye, dear.

138
00:07:32,519 --> 00:07:35,020
Come on, Clavdia!
You'll be late!

139
00:07:35,021 --> 00:07:36,523
You're my brother,
not my guardian.

140
00:07:37,023 --> 00:07:38,525
Mind your business.

141
00:07:41,528 --> 00:07:43,028
Good morning, Clavdia.

142
00:07:43,029 --> 00:07:45,030
Good morning, Marina.

143
00:07:45,031 --> 00:07:46,031
You're early.

144
00:07:46,032 --> 00:07:48,034
Oh! You know I never
eat breakfast.

145
00:07:49,536 --> 00:07:51,537
You always look so clean.

146
00:07:51,538 --> 00:07:53,539
You're no cleaner than I am.

147
00:07:53,540 --> 00:07:56,542
Maybe not as clean.
And hair is curly.

148
00:07:56,543 --> 00:07:58,043
Your hair looks nice.

149
00:07:58,044 --> 00:08:00,046
Oh, it's as straight as wheat.

150
00:08:00,547 --> 00:08:02,549
And don't try to console me.

151
00:08:06,052 --> 00:08:07,052
Well, well.

152
00:08:07,053 --> 00:08:09,555
The last day of school
is a happy day.

153
00:08:09,556 --> 00:08:10,556
Even I remember.

154
00:08:10,557 --> 00:08:12,057
Oh, no. No?

155
00:08:12,058 --> 00:08:14,060
We're very sorry
it's the last day.

156
00:08:56,102 --> 00:08:58,103
My first words will
be to congratulate

157
00:08:58,104 --> 00:09:00,606
our three pupils
in the last class

158
00:09:00,607 --> 00:09:02,608
who have all been
awarded scholarships

159
00:09:02,609 --> 00:09:05,112
to the state
University of Kiev.

160
00:09:06,613 --> 00:09:09,615
One of those three has
taken the highest marks

161
00:09:09,616 --> 00:09:13,620
of any pupil in this
year's senior graduating class.

162
00:09:14,120 --> 00:09:16,122
He is Damian Taratsa.

163
00:09:23,630 --> 00:09:29,635
It is not my custom to start
your vacation with a lecture.

164
00:09:29,636 --> 00:09:34,640
But this is the summer
of 1941, a solemn time.

165
00:09:34,641 --> 00:09:37,144
No one of us knows
what will happen.

166
00:09:38,645 --> 00:09:40,147
I don't have to remind you

167
00:09:40,148 --> 00:09:44,149
that we are people
with a noble history.

168
00:09:44,150 --> 00:09:46,652
You are expected to
carry on that history

169
00:09:46,653 --> 00:09:50,657
with complete devotion
and self-sacrifice.

170
00:09:51,157 --> 00:09:53,159
I think you'll do that.

171
00:09:54,160 --> 00:09:57,664
And now... Have a happy summer.

